<p>The number seven has a very special place in human consciousness. It has appeared in almost every culture, religion, and field of science throughout history. This integer, which seems simple, has fascinated people from ancient Mesopotamian astronomers to modern quantum physicists. It has become a part of human understanding in ways that go beyond coincidence. This number phenomenon shows an interesting connection between ancient knowledge and modern scientific discovery. For example, the seven visible celestial bodies that guided early civilizations and the seven colors that Newton found in white light.</p>

<h2>The Ancient Foundation: Seven Stars That Move Around</h2>

<p>People have respected seven since the first time they looked at the night sky. Seven celestial bodies that moved against the background of fixed stars were known to ancient civilizations all over the world. These were the Sun, Moon, Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter, and Saturn. These "wandering stars" formed the basis for humanity's first systematic understanding of cosmic order, leading to the seven-day week that still governs our modern calendar.</p>

